what does a sievert really mean

00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:09.080
in terms of increased risk?

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:11.810
Usually means the
increased risk of some sort

00:04:11.810 --> 00:04:15.650
of long-term biological
effect, whether it's cancer

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:18.740
or some other genetic
effects-- let's say mutations--

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:21.320
anything that would take
a while to manifest,

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:24.760
and would manifest by slow
but steady cell division.

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.200
And if you notice the
difference between adults

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:29.730
and whole population,
let's see--

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:36.240
yeah, sorry.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:37.710
You can see right
here that these--

00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:39.330
not very much dose.

00:04:39.330 --> 00:04:41.250
Let's say in the realm
of 10 to the minus 2

00:04:41.250 --> 00:04:44.430
sieverts can give you some
increased risk for cancer

00:04:44.430 --> 00:04:45.720
or some other effect.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.110
So we're talking on the
realm of 40 millisieverts

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:51.700
or so would give you some
additional cancer risk.

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:53.400
That's not a lot of dose.

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:55.920
That's up to about the limit
of the occupational dose

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:57.528
that you're allowed.

00:04:57.528 --> 00:04:59.320
So when we talk about
how much is too much,

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:02.340
I've taken some excerpts
from this Committee

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:04.650
