00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:29.830
And then how much is too much?

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:34.060
Let's say for the general public
for a background for excluding

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:37.300
things like natural background
and medical exposures,

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:40.000
you're not supposed to get about
more than one millisievert just

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:41.500
walking about outside.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:44.860
And you don't tend to
get that much more.

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:47.470
Why are medical exposures not
included, despite them being

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:49.781
pretty radioactive procedures?

00:07:49.781 --> 00:07:50.281
Yeah?

00:07:50.281 --> 00:07:52.149
AUDIENCE: Because
they're very targeted.

00:07:54.485 --> 00:07:55.860
MICHAEL SHORT:
They are targeted,

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:58.230
and so they could give a lot
of dose to certain organs.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:00.540
But the amount of
dose isn't necessarily

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:03.240
why we don't count
medical procedures.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:05.016
Anyone have any idea?

00:08:05.016 --> 00:08:05.796
Yeah.

00:08:05.796 --> 00:08:08.004
AUDIENCE: Was it because
usually you wear a lead vest

00:08:08.004 --> 00:08:09.690
if you're getting an X-ray?

00:08:09.690 --> 00:08:12.190
MICHAEL SHORT: In some cases,
like if you go to the dentist,

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:13.190
you'll get a lead X-ray.

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:17.200
But let's say you
get a chest X-ray.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:21.400
Why don't we care that a chest
X-ray is way more than you get?

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:23.840
Because these things
tend to save lives.

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:28.090
So you're absolutely willing
to get extra radiation exposure

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:30.640
that may have a delayed effect
if the immediate effect is

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:32.520
to save your life.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:33.570
You had a question?

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:35.539
Or no.

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:36.159
OK.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:37.830
Yeah, so we don't
count medical things

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:41.500
because chances are you're
doing them to improve or save

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:42.000
your life.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:43.860
So what's a little
bit of radiation

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:46.800
compared to let's say finding
the blood clot or the aneurysm

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:48.600
or whatever it would take?

00:08:51.140 --> 00:08:52.310
And then how much is enough?

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:53.932
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
that's the table.

00:08:53.932 --> 00:08:56.390
MICHAEL SHORT: This is the
table that you're familiar with?

00:08:56.390 --> 00:08:56.890
Yeah.

00:08:56.890 --> 00:08:58.910
They actually talk about
