00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:18.170
of the reactor.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:22.460
But the lens of the eye can take
a fair bit more dose per unit

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:24.890
mass than the whole body.

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:28.260
The lens of the eye is not a
particularly fast developing

00:09:28.260 --> 00:09:28.760
tissue.

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:32.390
It can cloud up with an insane
amount of radiation exposure.

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:35.450
That would take a lot more
than 150 millisieverts to do,

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:36.200
though.

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:37.970
And then things like
500 millisieverts

00:09:37.970 --> 00:09:39.680
for skin, hands, feet.

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.260
Pretty much just groups of
muscle, bone, and dead skin

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:46.250
that not much is
going on biologically.

00:09:46.250 --> 00:09:49.000
Blood's flowing through
it, but that's about it.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.150
And notice that the regulations
do differ a little bit,

00:09:53.150 --> 00:09:55.280
but on the whole,
they're fairly similar.

00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:58.310
Same for the eye, same for
the feet, same for the year.

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:00.030
Cumulative is a
little different.

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:02.420
This says 10
millisieverts times age.

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:04.358
This allows you a
little bit more.

00:10:04.358 --> 00:10:05.900
Whichever recommendations
you follow,

00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:08.000
they're all pretty similar.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:09.710
And our knowledge
of how much dose

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:12.260
leads to how much
risk hasn't changed

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:15.440
a ton in the last decade or so.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:18.280
There's been all sorts of
arguments for or against it.

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:21.020
Has anyone heard of this
LNT or Linear No Threshold

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:24.893
model of dose versus risk?

00:10:24.893 --> 00:10:26.310
This is something
we'll talk a lot

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:27.690
about on the last day of class.

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:29.490
This is the theory
that the amount

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:32.070
of risk versus the
amount of dose is linear.

00:10:32.070 --> 00:10:35.580
And no threshold means that
every little bit of dose

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.230
gives you additional risk.

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:41.580
This is not supported
very much by science.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:43.950
I'd say it's not
supported by science.

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.980
The converse argument is also
not supported by science.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:49.980
We just don't have the
statistics at super low doses

00:10:49.980 --> 00:10:51.720
to say what happens.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:55.260
But the official recommendation
is that there is a unit of dose

00:10:55.260 --> 00:11:01.840
that we define as nothing,
and it's 0.01 millisieverts--

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:06.050
about 100 bananas--
per event, let's say--

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:09.730
yeah, where does it say--
yeah, per source or practice.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:11.950
So eating 100 bananas
in one sitting

00:11:11.950 --> 00:11:15.100
is considered to give you
zero additional risk according

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.840
to the official guidelines.

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:18.610
So the guidelines
put in place do not

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:20.680
follow the linear
no threshold model.

