00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:09.160
I've seen some
documentary such things

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:11.770
and don't call this a science
that say, oh 10 to the 40 years

00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:13.840
from now, the last
protons decay,

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:16.810
or the last whatever
elements decay

00:23:16.810 --> 00:23:19.490
into all protons and neutrons.

00:23:19.490 --> 00:23:21.220
Don't know if
that's true, but it

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:24.460
does make me wonder, are some
of the other so-called stable

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:28.670
elements just have
ridiculously long half lives?

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:31.268
It's something to think about.

00:23:31.268 --> 00:23:33.640
So let's take a look at
the building materials,

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:37.150
and see what's in the typical
things around us right now.

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:40.120
You can see how much
granite, radioactive thorium,

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:42.550
and potassium are in
these building materials.

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:46.410
And how many usually is
measured in picocuries per gram.

00:23:46.410 --> 00:23:49.870
A picocurie is already less
than a becquerel per gram.

00:23:49.870 --> 00:23:57.000
Because a curie is what, 3.7
times 10 to the 10 becquerels.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.720
And a pico is a 10
to the minus 12.

00:23:59.720 --> 00:24:03.180
So things on the order of
a few picocuries per gram,

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:04.690
a gram of that
material might emit

00:24:04.690 --> 00:24:07.360
one disintegration per second.

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:09.100
Not a lot of radiation.

00:24:09.100 --> 00:24:11.920
But take a look at how much
potassium there is in granite.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:16.060
Nanocuries per gram, that's
getting into the integers

00:24:16.060 --> 00:24:18.130
worth of becquerels.

00:24:18.130 --> 00:24:22.620
If you look at wood,
check that out.

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:25.844
Anyone heard of potash before?

00:24:25.844 --> 00:24:27.830
It's one of the ways
we get potassium.

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:31.180
So if you take wood based things
and you burn them in a fire,

00:24:31.180 --> 00:24:33.130
you drive off all the
carbon in the water,

00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:36.460
you're left with these kind of
whitened salt and pepper ashes.

00:24:36.460 --> 00:24:37.390
That's potash.

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.040
That's the ashes
left over in the pot

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:40.332
after you burn stuff in a fire.

00:24:40.332 --> 00:24:42.202
They're quite potassium rich.

00:24:42.202 --> 00:24:43.660
So I think what
we'll do next year,

00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:45.662
instead of burning
a bunch of food,

00:24:45.662 --> 00:24:46.870
is just burn a bunch of wood.

00:24:46.870 --> 00:24:50.290
We'll have a nice bonfire,
collect the ashes.

00:24:50.290 --> 00:24:53.080
And we can see how much
potassium there is in wood.

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:55.270
Which pound for pound,
if you see on this list,

00:24:55.270 --> 00:24:58.390
is the most radioactive
building material there is.

00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.270
Just that wood happens
to be pretty inexpensive,

00:25:01.270 --> 00:25:05.050
and consists mostly of water,
lignin, and other carboniferous

00:25:05.050 --> 00:25:06.340
materials.

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:08.200
They don't have
carbon-14 on this list,

00:25:08.200 --> 00:25:10.200
but let's take a look at
some of the other ones.

00:25:10.200 --> 00:25:14.560
So sandstone cement has a
pretty toasty signature to it.

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:17.500
Gypsum drywall.

00:25:17.500 --> 00:25:20.470
What is it, 13 parts per million
uranium in all the drywall

00:25:20.470 --> 00:25:22.830
you tend to find.

00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:24.075
Anyone scared yet?

00:25:24.075 --> 00:25:26.140
Because you shouldn't be.

