00:25:50.470 --> 00:25:54.150
Seawater is another great
source of radioactivity.

00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:58.410
Enough so that
people have actually

00:25:58.410 --> 00:26:03.125
proposed harvesting
uranium from seawater.

00:26:03.125 --> 00:26:05.000
So the total amount of
activity in the ocean,

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.140
there's something
like 11 exabecquerels

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:12.440
of radiation contained in
the uranium in the seawater.

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:16.220
Which means you should be able
to have a gigantic trawler

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:20.208
flying out around in the
ocean, and just floating

00:26:20.208 --> 00:26:22.250
through the seawater,
picking up atoms of uranium

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:22.670
here and there.

00:26:22.670 --> 00:26:24.503
Because technically,
there's enough to power

00:26:24.503 --> 00:26:26.300
the world for like 2,000 years.

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:28.410
The problem is the ocean is big.

00:26:28.410 --> 00:26:30.920
It doesn't stop people from
actually working on it.

00:26:30.920 --> 00:26:32.337
So it's neat to
think that there's

00:26:32.337 --> 00:26:34.430
a whole lot of
carbon-14 and tritium

00:26:34.430 --> 00:26:37.650
and uranium in seawater.

00:26:37.650 --> 00:26:39.690
300 picocuries per liter.

00:26:39.690 --> 00:26:42.598
Anyone have any idea why there's
so much more potassium activity

00:26:42.598 --> 00:26:43.890
than anything else in seawater?

00:26:47.590 --> 00:26:49.330
It's because it's salty, yeah.

00:26:49.330 --> 00:26:50.950
And potassium's
just like sodium.

00:26:50.950 --> 00:26:53.380
So there'll be a
fair bit of potassium

00:26:53.380 --> 00:27:00.300
in the seawater, 0.0117%
of which is potassium-40.

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:04.030
And so last year, people asked,
what, uranium from seawater?

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:05.360
How is that even possible?

00:27:05.360 --> 00:27:07.090
So this is the part
in the course where

00:27:07.090 --> 00:27:09.250
I'm going to pull out a
lot more recent papers

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:11.920
to show you some of the
cooler innovations going on.

00:27:11.920 --> 00:27:14.290
So you could use this adsorbent.

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:15.000
And adsorbent.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:20.060
Does anyone know what adsorption
means, not absorption?

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:21.890
Adsorption is when
something sticks

00:27:21.890 --> 00:27:23.630
to the surface of something.

00:27:23.630 --> 00:27:25.880
Absorption with a B is
when it actually gets

00:27:25.880 --> 00:27:27.950
incorporated into the bulk.

00:27:27.950 --> 00:27:30.500
So folks are thinking about
making high surface area

00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:35.280
materials that can adsorb
selectively atoms of uranium.

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:39.560
So you send out this huge
braided net, or a huge stack

00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:44.240
of adsorbing material with
a D, and just go around

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:45.590
in the ocean.

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:48.440
Attach them to tankers
or cargo ships,

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:50.810
and just have them
pull in product

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:53.150
as they go from coast to coast.

00:27:53.150 --> 00:27:56.180
And by actually changing around
the chemistry and the geometry

00:27:56.180 --> 00:27:59.300
of this, you can enhance
things specifically for uranium

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:00.830
by about a factor of three.

00:28:00.830 --> 00:28:03.800
And this yellowcake right
here next to an actual ruler--

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:05.930
that's 50 millimeters
right there--

00:28:05.930 --> 00:28:08.600
that was obtained
directly from seawater.

00:28:08.600 --> 00:28:11.938
So you can actually pull
yellowcake out of the ocean.

00:28:11.938 --> 00:28:12.980
Just not very much of it.

00:28:15.580 --> 00:28:18.810
And the way these work is there
are interesting compounds that

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:22.530
selectively absorb uranium
into their structure,

00:28:22.530 --> 00:28:27.990
not by direct chemical bonding,
but by getting something close.

00:28:27.990 --> 00:28:30.990
For example, my wife tends
to study metals bonding

00:28:30.990 --> 00:28:31.740
to proteins.

00:28:31.740 --> 00:28:34.488
And it's not necessarily
always a full chemical bond

00:28:34.488 --> 00:28:36.030
like you might think,
but the protein

00:28:36.030 --> 00:28:39.570
can kind of wrap around a
metal ion, transport it places.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:41.530
Similar thing going here.

00:28:41.530 --> 00:28:43.590
I'm not going to
pontificate anymore

00:28:43.590 --> 00:28:46.200
on it because the title
has the word organic in it,

00:28:46.200 --> 00:28:48.380
and I am definitely
not an organic chemist.

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:49.963
Don't want to tell
you anything wrong,

00:28:49.963 --> 00:28:52.583
but I do want to tell you you
can actually see this paper

00:28:52.583 --> 00:28:54.000
to find out what
sort of compounds

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.958
selectively grab onto uranium.

00:28:55.958 --> 00:28:57.750
And if there's a seawater
floating through,

00:28:57.750 --> 00:29:01.200
and uranium happens to flow
nearby, it can bond to it.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:05.040
You can then somehow squeeze
out or burn off that adsorbent,

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:07.535
and there you get uranium.

00:29:07.535 --> 00:29:09.160
Now let's talk about
what's in the body

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:13.720
and interpreting the spectra
that you got from EHS,

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:15.270
your full body spectra.

00:29:15.270 --> 00:29:16.870
If you take a look
at how much uranium

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:19.030
there is in the body,
wow, there's some.

00:29:19.030 --> 00:29:22.330
Every one of you is got
about a becquerel of uranium

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:23.480
in the body.

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:27.080
But if you look at the relative
amounts, rate it was at.

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:29.870
The only things that
really matter a ton,

00:29:29.870 --> 00:29:34.580
potassium-40, about 4.4
kilobecquerels per human.

00:29:34.580 --> 00:29:38.490
So each of you is giving
off 4,400 potassium gammas

00:29:38.490 --> 00:29:40.080
per second.

00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:42.770
Most of them just flow right
through all the other people.

00:29:42.770 --> 00:29:48.183
And then carbon-14,
about 3.7 kilobecquerels.

00:29:48.183 --> 00:29:50.600
Pretty interesting to know
just how much radioactive stuff

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:52.070
you have in your own body.

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:55.310
You will need this table
for homework number eight

