00:32:56.830 --> 00:32:59.575
on any sort of airport
radiation monitor.

00:32:59.575 --> 00:33:01.450
So again, if you ever
get a medical procedure

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:03.730
with any sort of
radiation, anything,

00:33:03.730 --> 00:33:08.260
do declare it, because
it's quite measurable.

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:10.390
Then there's radiation
from altitude.

00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:13.210
I may have mentioned already
that the reason that pilots

00:33:13.210 --> 00:33:16.810
can't fly for a certain number
of hours is not fatigue,

00:33:16.810 --> 00:33:18.940
but it's radiation exposure.

00:33:18.940 --> 00:33:21.400
When you start to
look at how many

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:25.750
microsieverts you get per
hour on the ground, 0.03.

00:33:25.750 --> 00:33:28.270
Right about down at that--
hanging around for an hour

00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:29.950
is a negligible dose.

00:33:29.950 --> 00:33:32.440
You go up to
international air travel,

00:33:32.440 --> 00:33:35.950
that goes up by a factor
of little more than 100.

00:33:35.950 --> 00:33:39.310
And so you get a fair bit
of radiation exposure.

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:42.160
If you take your annual
allowable occupational

00:33:42.160 --> 00:33:47.160
limit of 50 millisieverts,
divide by 3.7 microsieverts,

00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:48.650
you're getting close to 86--

00:33:48.650 --> 00:33:49.150
what is it?

00:33:49.150 --> 00:33:51.948
How many hours in a year?

00:33:51.948 --> 00:33:52.970
Let's see.

00:33:52.970 --> 00:33:55.860
There's three times 10 of
the seven seconds in a year.

00:33:55.860 --> 00:33:57.640
So divide that by 3,600.

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:59.680
That's getting on
the realm of 10,000.

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:01.690
That's about the
conversion factor.

