00:35:13.690 --> 00:35:17.230
and have cell phones, and don't
want to have a fake time bomb,

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:19.390
you can actually hook
in your Geiger counter

00:35:19.390 --> 00:35:21.330
to the microphone port
of your cell phone.

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:23.230
And with a few available
radiation apps,

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:27.220
you can actually monitor
your dose in microsieverts.

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:29.710
Assuming that it all comes
from gamma rays, which

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:31.880
is most of what a lot of
cosmic rays will produce.

00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:33.430
So it's a pretty
safe approximation

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:35.650
that your dose in gray
flying on the plane

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:37.600
is also your dose in
sieverts, because it's

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:39.933
whole body, and its gammas.

00:35:39.933 --> 00:35:41.350
So I'd say try
this at home, kids.

00:35:41.350 --> 00:35:46.130
This is one of those things
I recommend you try out.

00:35:46.130 --> 00:35:48.830
Speaking of these cosmic rays,
where did they come from?

00:35:48.830 --> 00:35:51.220
Well, this is a question
that's been under debate,

00:35:51.220 --> 00:35:54.910
and was more completely
answered just a few years ago.

00:35:54.910 --> 00:35:58.330
They come from very high energy
particles from somewhere.

00:35:58.330 --> 00:36:01.060
It had been argued, do they
come mostly from solar flares,

00:36:01.060 --> 00:36:04.480
or did they come from
elsewhere in the galaxy?

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:07.810
Mostly we're talking about
things like high energy protons

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:09.640
or other charged particles.

00:36:09.640 --> 00:36:11.710
We're also talking neutrinos.

00:36:11.710 --> 00:36:13.330
Anyone know about
how many neutrinos

00:36:13.330 --> 00:36:18.790
are theorized to pass
through you every second?

00:36:18.790 --> 00:36:19.690
Trillions.

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:21.110
Yeah, something like that.

00:36:21.110 --> 00:36:23.800
But they basically don't
interact with matter.

00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:25.760
As I showed you guys
near the beginning,

00:36:25.760 --> 00:36:29.710
it takes a gigantic salt mine
full of water and exploding

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:33.250
photomultiplier tubes in order
to catch two or three neutrinos

00:36:33.250 --> 00:36:34.330
a day if you're lucky.

00:36:34.330 --> 00:36:36.430
So let's say those
don't really matter

00:36:36.430 --> 00:36:38.020
in terms of background dose.

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:41.218
But when those high
energy particles interact

00:36:41.218 --> 00:36:43.510
with the oxygen and nitrogen
up here in the atmosphere,

00:36:43.510 --> 00:36:46.030
they produce a
shower and cascade

00:36:46.030 --> 00:36:50.850
of additional ionization
and high energy particles.

00:36:50.850 --> 00:36:54.870
So it's been said that solar
flares and such will accelerate

00:36:54.870 --> 00:36:57.210
charged particles
from the plasma

00:36:57.210 --> 00:36:58.890
in the sun towards Earth.

00:36:58.890 --> 00:37:02.100
They're deflected somewhat
by the magnetic field

00:37:02.100 --> 00:37:05.510
of the Earth, but they
tend to enter right here

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:07.250
at the-- what is it?

00:37:07.250 --> 00:37:08.070
At the poles.

00:37:08.070 --> 00:37:11.210
I'm sorry, that's the simple
word I was looking for.

00:37:11.210 --> 00:37:16.820
Until recently in 2001, they
were looking specifically

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:19.910
at the evidence for or against
the idea that coronal mass

00:37:19.910 --> 00:37:22.820
ejections-- which means
large ejections of mass from

00:37:22.820 --> 00:37:25.760
the outer layers, these
sparcer layers of the sun--

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:30.080
was responsible for most charged
particles and cosmic rays.

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:32.110
Skipping the stuff
that's not in bold,

00:37:32.110 --> 00:37:34.970
it appears to be that
the CME bow shock

00:37:34.970 --> 00:37:37.250
scenario has been overvalued.

00:37:37.250 --> 00:37:38.720
So for a while,
folks were saying

00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:42.020
most cosmic rays come from the
sun-- that's our nearest star.

00:37:42.020 --> 00:37:46.250
By making really, really careful
measurements of the energy

00:37:46.250 --> 00:37:47.690
and lifetime of
these cosmic rays,

00:37:47.690 --> 00:37:49.970
this has actually been
somewhat disproven

00:37:49.970 --> 00:37:52.970
that this is the major
source of cosmic rays, which

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:54.810
is pretty cool.

00:37:54.810 --> 00:37:57.560
But let's talk about where
they actually come from.

00:37:57.560 --> 00:38:00.530
Reactions that you can
probably understand.

00:38:00.530 --> 00:38:03.290
So extremely high protons
enter the atmosphere.

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:05.660
They all start as
high energy protons.

00:38:05.660 --> 00:38:08.150
And when protons are
high enough energy--

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:10.430
and like I do probably
in every class ever,

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:13.900
I'm going to pull up Janis
to show you something.

00:38:13.900 --> 00:38:16.690
They can undergo what's
called spallation.

00:38:16.690 --> 00:38:19.570
It's the same principle
that the Spallation Neutron

00:38:19.570 --> 00:38:21.910
Source at Oak Ridge
National Lab works on

00:38:21.910 --> 00:38:24.610
is shoot in extremely
high energy protons,

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:26.690
out come neutrons.

00:38:26.690 --> 00:38:30.370
So as usual, it didn't
clone the screen right.

00:38:30.370 --> 00:38:31.690
So just bear with me for a sec.

