00:38:50.710 --> 00:38:54.270
we'll go to the
incident proton data.

00:38:54.270 --> 00:38:57.920
We'll stick with
the same library.

00:38:57.920 --> 00:38:59.360
Let's see how much they have.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:02.880
Not much, but enough to
matter, because there's

00:39:02.880 --> 00:39:07.240
a lot of nitrogen-14
up in the air.

00:39:07.240 --> 00:39:11.930
Let's see what happens when
protons hit nitrogen-14

00:39:11.930 --> 00:39:13.180
all the way at high energy.

00:39:13.180 --> 00:39:16.910
So don't quite know what a
negative cross-section refers

00:39:16.910 --> 00:39:17.410
to.

00:39:17.410 --> 00:39:22.190
But at high energies, this is
definitely a possible event.

00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:24.540
And let's see, there's not
a lot of cross-sections

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:26.160
to look at here.

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:28.670
Let's try oxygen-16.

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:30.620
Not much.

00:39:30.620 --> 00:39:32.760
We'll stick to the slides then.

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:35.520
So when a high energy
proton strikes a nucleus,

00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:37.290
it can eject neutrons.

00:39:37.290 --> 00:39:41.790
And those neutrons can then
cause activation reactions,

00:39:41.790 --> 00:39:44.820
and then emit things like
proton or tritium, leading to--

00:39:44.820 --> 00:39:47.100
that's where your
carbon-14 comes from.

00:39:47.100 --> 00:39:49.110
Comes from nitrogen-14.

00:39:49.110 --> 00:39:52.350
So in comes a high energy
proton, releases a neutron.

00:39:52.350 --> 00:39:56.550
That neutron hits nitrogen-14,
releases a proton,

00:39:56.550 --> 00:39:58.630
out comes carbon-14.

00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:01.170
So this is why it's being
constantly generated

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:02.020
in the atmosphere.

00:40:02.020 --> 00:40:03.812
It's not like there's
a certain amount that

00:40:03.812 --> 00:40:06.270
was there at the beginning
of the universe and decays,

00:40:06.270 --> 00:40:09.150
because its half life
is only 5,700 years.

00:40:09.150 --> 00:40:11.370
So this is part of why
radiocarbon dating works,

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:13.615
because we have cosmic rays.

00:40:13.615 --> 00:40:15.240
It's kind of a neat
connection to make.

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:17.323
If there weren't cosmic
rays, all of the carbon-14

00:40:17.323 --> 00:40:21.720
would decay pretty quickly
in the universe time scale.

00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:25.350
And we wouldn't have this
form of radiocarbon dating.

00:40:25.350 --> 00:40:28.320
And then same thing for tritium
production in the atmosphere.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:30.830
This is where some of that
tritium naturally comes from,

00:40:30.830 --> 00:40:33.530
is it makes carbon-12-- which
is the normal form of carbon--

00:40:33.530 --> 00:40:36.080
but out come tritium,
which there is going

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:38.750
to be some constant isotopic
fraction of tritium in all

00:40:38.750 --> 00:40:40.760
the world's hydrogen.
Some of it's being

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:43.670
generated in real time.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:45.860
And we do have these
spallation sources on Earth.

00:40:45.860 --> 00:40:48.500
Like I mentioned, the
Spallation Neutron Source

00:40:48.500 --> 00:40:50.570
has a gigantic synchrotron.

00:40:50.570 --> 00:40:53.930
We've seen these before, which
just injects in this case

00:40:53.930 --> 00:40:58.100
protons, which circle around and
around and around, accelerating

00:40:58.100 --> 00:41:02.570
until some of them are
extracted and fire onto things

00:41:02.570 --> 00:41:06.740
like a liquid mercury target,
some neutron rich liquid metal.

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:09.050
So you want something
that's very neutron rich.

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:10.970
You want something
that's very dense.

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:13.670
You want something that's fluid
so you can cool it better.

00:41:13.670 --> 00:41:16.070
And you want something with
high thermal conductivity.

00:41:16.070 --> 00:41:17.990
That's where the metal comes in.

00:41:17.990 --> 00:41:20.420
So a liquid metal you can
keep cool really well.

00:41:20.420 --> 00:41:23.900
Because when you're firing lots
of 800 MeV protons into it,

00:41:23.900 --> 00:41:26.795
you generate a tremendous
amount of heat.

00:41:26.795 --> 00:41:28.670
And this is what the
actual thing looks like.

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:30.980
You can get tours of
this down in Tennessee

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:32.948
at the Oak Ridge National Lab.

00:41:32.948 --> 00:41:34.490
Actually, I've driven
up here before.

00:41:34.490 --> 00:41:36.350
I recognize this from the map.

00:41:36.350 --> 00:41:38.680
That's pretty cool.

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:40.560
So where the actual
neutron science stuff

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:42.580
happens, where all
the scientists sit

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:44.580
with their targets, there's
quite a bit of stuff

00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:46.050
going on behind it.

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:47.910
So there is a gigantic--

00:41:47.910 --> 00:41:50.960
you can see that's a
parking lot for scale.

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:54.420
There's a gigantic
linear accelerator

00:41:54.420 --> 00:41:57.090
shooting into the
synchrotron ring, which

00:41:57.090 --> 00:41:59.130
then fires the protons
here into the target

00:41:59.130 --> 00:42:03.720
into one of any number of end
stations, which creates a not

00:42:03.720 --> 00:42:07.230
quite push button, but
turn on-able pulsed neutron

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:09.220
source, which is pretty slick.

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:11.880
And again, parking
lot for scale.

00:42:11.880 --> 00:42:14.410
Takes a lot of magnets to
bend an 800 MeV proton.

00:42:16.722 --> 00:42:18.180
That's what it
actually looks like.

00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:21.670
Has anyone ever seen one
of these synchrotrons?

00:42:21.670 --> 00:42:24.525
Like at Brookhaven or at
Oak Ridge or at anywhere?

00:42:24.525 --> 00:42:25.900
They're quite
interesting things.

00:42:25.900 --> 00:42:28.570
The closest one
to us is the NSLS,

00:42:28.570 --> 00:42:30.700
or the National Synchrotron
Light Source version

00:42:30.700 --> 00:42:32.620
two at Brookhaven National Lab.

00:42:32.620 --> 00:42:34.973
It's like a 2 and 1/2 hour
drive down in Long Island.

00:42:34.973 --> 00:42:36.640
I don't know if they're
doing tours yet,

00:42:36.640 --> 00:42:38.770
but it's about a
kilometer around.

00:42:38.770 --> 00:42:40.780
And I was told they did
bike races around it

00:42:40.780 --> 00:42:42.447
to see who could beat
the protons, which

00:42:42.447 --> 00:42:44.920
of course everybody loses.

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:47.200
But they are pretty
insane collections

00:42:47.200 --> 00:42:48.970
of magnets, vacuum equipment.

