Complete insanity can happen
with super high energy

00:44:18.740 --> 00:44:19.890
electrons.

00:44:19.890 --> 00:44:23.520
We've already talked
about Bremsstrahlung.

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:26.220
We have talked about
synchrotron radiation, where

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:29.170
you have a charged particle
going along a magnetic field

00:44:29.170 --> 00:44:29.670
line.

00:44:29.670 --> 00:44:33.190
It changes direction
and gives off X-rays.

00:44:33.190 --> 00:44:37.660
We haven't talked about
inverse Compton scattering.

00:44:37.660 --> 00:44:40.465
Interesting process here.

00:44:40.465 --> 00:44:43.550
In comes a low energy
photon, hits an electron,

00:44:43.550 --> 00:44:47.090
out comes a higher
energy photon.

00:44:47.090 --> 00:44:49.340
Compton scatterings usually
think of as the other way

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:53.330
around, where a high energy
photon comes in, scatters off

00:44:53.330 --> 00:44:55.880
an electron, loses energy.

00:44:55.880 --> 00:44:58.190
In this case, a
high energy electron

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:00.410
colliding with a
low energy photon

00:45:00.410 --> 00:45:04.858
can impart energy to the photon.

00:45:04.858 --> 00:45:06.900
And you can actually
calculate-- or in this case,

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:08.600
I've just taken from a paper--

00:45:08.600 --> 00:45:12.140
the energy gain from
inverse Compton scattering,

00:45:12.140 --> 00:45:15.410
as well as whatever
cross-section there is.

00:45:15.410 --> 00:45:18.020
And even though this is a
very infrequent process--

00:45:18.020 --> 00:45:19.825
well, the universe
is pretty big,

00:45:19.825 --> 00:45:21.200
and contains a
lot of things that

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:24.320
have magnetic fields
like stars and black--

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:27.880
whatever else happens
to have magnetic fields.

00:45:27.880 --> 00:45:29.630
And you can identify
radio sources

00:45:29.630 --> 00:45:33.050
by looking for these inverse
Compton scattered X-rays.

00:45:33.050 --> 00:45:36.030
So the Chandra X-ray map,
I believe a piece of which

00:45:36.030 --> 00:45:40.190
or a receiver for which is up in
the building in Porter Square.

00:45:40.190 --> 00:45:42.930
If you guys go down three
stops on the red line,

00:45:42.930 --> 00:45:45.530
you'll see this little area
full of Japanese noodle

00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:48.197
shops, Lesley University,
a bunch of galleries.

00:45:48.197 --> 00:45:48.905
And in a little--

00:45:51.742 --> 00:45:54.200
I think it's still there-- and
a little sign that says, oh,

00:45:54.200 --> 00:45:57.080
and there's the Chandra
X-ray Observatory.

00:45:57.080 --> 00:45:57.668
Whatever.

00:45:57.668 --> 00:45:59.210
They may or may not
have moved, but I

00:45:59.210 --> 00:46:02.430
recommend you check it out.

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:04.570
And then what happens
to those electrons?

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:08.180
Well, they can actually decay.

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:09.840
Pretty interesting things.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:12.080
And so some of this
inverse Compton scattering

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:15.080
has gone into the evidence
for or against where

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:17.690
cosmic rays come from,
because you should

00:46:17.690 --> 00:46:21.080
see electrons of
a certain energy

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:22.925
after undergoing this process.

00:46:25.850 --> 00:46:27.020
I think I will skip ahead.

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:28.530
Oh, I won't skip ahead.

00:46:28.530 --> 00:46:32.010
And so what these
cosmic rays can produce

00:46:32.010 --> 00:46:35.190
is what's called positive,
negative, or neutral pions.

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:37.860
Other subatomic particles
with masses somewhere

00:46:37.860 --> 00:46:40.860
between protons and
electrons that themselves

00:46:40.860 --> 00:46:44.440
can undergo different reactions
or different decays into muons.

00:46:44.440 --> 00:46:46.170
And don't worry, muons
and pions and such

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:48.270
are not part of the
topic of this course.

00:46:48.270 --> 00:46:50.640
But they do have
known lifetimes,

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:52.782
they do have known
masses and charges,

00:46:52.782 --> 00:46:54.240
they do have known
stopping powers.

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:56.040
We should be able
to measure them.

00:46:56.040 --> 00:46:59.160
And there is a cosmic muon
detector at Boston University.

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:01.290
Or rather, it's a
pair of detectors

00:47:01.290 --> 00:47:03.690
that looks for this
coincidence of one muon

00:47:03.690 --> 00:47:06.150
scattering off one
detector, or interacting,

00:47:06.150 --> 00:47:08.970
